author: _blackcrow
body:
I'm quite sure the price before the split and before 2019 end was under valued. <$300? 

The ridiculous amount of cash they hold, the high margins for their products, holding a specific % of the entire global mobile market of which they hold on to both the software and the hardware, on top of that, the entire software distribution business that sits on these devices. 

Which gets replaced every 2 years. More or less. You get android switchers who comes back in a cycle or two. 

Just think about the monthly revenue from the app store, and other services. The games you play that requires a payment in game, Apple just tax those payments at 30% by providing the resourses for distributing it on the app store etc etc.

That adds up to crazy amount of revenue. The whole market evaluating their tech and expecting their downfall each and every time they release their new phones are really missing it. The whole market for the high end mobile phones only has a couple of players, and only ONE in the entire industry that holds the keys to both software, hardware eco system which includes the OS and the distribution platform. 

That's not including the rest of the eco system of iPads, Apple watch, pen, Macs, air pods. These are all high margin products mind you and they are sold at a high volume. And of course they are consistently best in class or considered to be, in order to command that pricing.  

It's almost as if Apple has a tax system on almost 10% or more of the global population, extremely reliable and consistent income. With no need for them to cut corners or reduce their profit margins.

Of course feel free to rebut me, after all I'm typing this out on the go on a cracked android device with two thumbs. A lot can go wrong.

author: cullenjwebb
body:
The advantages in the situation you describe could be one of the following:

* PayPal has found a way to cut down on costs / regulations by allowing users to transfer funds via Crypto which is then converted into local fiat currency, rather than converting from fiat to fiat, or even within a single fiat currency
* This opens the door for Crypto spending on regular everyday purchases. Paypal is extremely popular in online stores and opens the door for Crypto users even if the seller doesn't plan on keeping the coin as-is
* Following up on the previous point, if more online shopping is conducted with Crypto it will encourage adoption and makes a future where online sellers want to keep the coin rather than convert them more likely as they could replenish stock with their Crypto or make other business purchases

Overall though the long-term goal is for Bitcoin / Crypto to mature enough and be user friendly so that 3rd party help isn't required. It has made impressive improvements over the last few years but I still don't trust my Mom / Dad / Others to know how to responsibly hold their keys so I'm glad that an option like this is available in the meantime.

author: NewYorkJewbag
body:
Okay my comment was removed because I mentioned a failed investment. I have edited my comment. 

You will not be disappointed. The newsletter I subscribe to is Stock Advisor is run by the two founders (brothers) and has a lot of variety. Some of their marketing can be over the top and click-baity, but don’t pay that any mind. You could also just check out their basic stock investing book. 

Some keys to their philosophy are:

1. You don’t need to be an expert or genius to grow wealth in the market. You need to be patient and unemotional (that’s harder than it sounds.)

2. You actually have an advantage over professional investors such as fund managers because you have a longer time horizon for investments to pay off (3-5 years) while the pros really can’t hold things that long with out seeing gains. 

3. They focus on buying companies, not buying stocks. They look at the brand, the ownership, the management, customer loyalty, their products, etc...

4. ...and that doesn’t mean they don’t look at the technical aspects of EPS, P/E, cash flow, etc, but they place those things in context of companies themselves. 

5. They reinforce that you only need to be right 51% of the time to beat the market (though for me they’ve been right more like 90% of the time.)

6. They do recommend beginners anchor their stock investments around ETFs to start. And fuck mutual funds.

You can probably look at the track record of their picks pretty easily. I will say this, towards the beginning of the pandemic, I went in on a total of 7 new investments. Even after the last weeks major sell off, I’m up 80% in 6 months for those. For reference, SPY is up about 50% from the dead bottom of the pandemic (I bought in a little above that so up more like 40% from when I bought.) And one of those companies went completely belly up (a Chinese coffee company that wasn’t just brewing Java, they were cooking the books, too.) 

God, I sound like I work for them, but I just have been so happy that I discovered them when I was younger (I’m 48, started with them in my early 30s) I like to share my experience.

author: ChrisNomad
body:
A couple of years ago I took my infant son and wife to a ‘big city’ back East for a vacation in the winter.

We’d used AirBNB once before and it went okay, so we thought we’d do it again for this two week trip.  With a baby and an extra sleeping space in the living room AirBNB fits a lot better than a hotel (ideally).

We found a killer looking condo in a brand new building, and the price was comparable with a hotel, but again with the added sleeping space, kitchen, room for the baby to crawl around, etc. it looked like a great deal.

However, when we got to the building the person that was supposed to meet us with the keys told us we had to go ‘walk’ into the parking garage under the building through the exit, go deep into the parking garage and find a lockbox with the keys.  THEN we were supposed to walk through the garage entrance to the building and we’re told we couldn’t walk through the front lobby.  As many of you are now thinking, we’re fucked.

It’s already late in the evening, we’ve been traveling for 14 hours (woke up at 3am to catch the flight), it’s snowing out, and we have an infant.  All the other hotels are now booked solid and we have to play this one out.

The keys don’t work to the downstairs so we end up calling the ‘contact’ and finally they come and show us how to get in.  We’ve already been in the freezing garage for an hour.  I was literally ready to strangle the guy when he walked up.

Needless to say we were able to make it all work in the end, the condo was killer, but it was obviously not okay with the building that they were renting short terms in AirBnB.

These types of rentals are going on all over in many cities and states.  Eventually, like Uber, AirBnB is going to have to follow the laws of the land, new laws and regulations will be made, and they won’t be able to keep throwing hundreds of millions battling lawsuits while they disrupt (or break laws) to turn a profit.

This is one area that absolutely hate with the business models of these upstarts.  Imagine I open up a business in your field and don’t follow any of the rules but just fight everything in courts and pay fines while you follow the rules and I break them.  As publicly traded companies this is going to have to get cleaned up.
